Current paper introduction: 
The Lambda Cold Dark Matter model provides a remarkably successful framework for understanding the formation and evolution of large-scale structure in the Universe. Cosmological N-body simulations are an indispensable tool for connecting this theoretical framework to observational data. By evolving the distribution of dark matter under gravity from early, nearly homogeneous conditions to the complex cosmic web we see today, these simulations provide the primary means of generating theoretical predictions in the deeply non-linear regime. As next-generation galaxy surveys promise to map the cosmos with unprecedented precision, the demand for accurate and statistically robust theoretical predictions has never been greater.

A significant challenge in modern cosmology is the immense computational cost associated with these simulations. To fully exploit the statistical power of upcoming surveys, we require not single simulations, but large ensembles containing hundreds or thousands of independent realizations. Such ensembles are essential for accurately estimating covariance matrices of cosmological observables, for training emulators that can rapidly explore parameter space, and for rigorously testing the impact of systematic effects. The computational expense of running traditional, high-resolution N-body codes on large supercomputing clusters presents a major bottleneck, limiting the scope and statistical certainty of many cosmological analyses.

To address this computational barrier, we turn to the massively parallel architecture of Graphics Processing Units (GPUs). The Particle-Mesh (PM) algorithm, which solves for gravitational forces on a grid, is particularly well-suited for GPU acceleration. While the PM method's resolution is limited by its grid size, it offers an excellent balance between computational speed and physical accuracy on the large scales most relevant to many cosmological studies. This makes it an ideal candidate for generating the large simulation volumes needed for statistical analyses where small-scale baryonic physics or halo substructure are not the primary focus.

In this paper, we present a new, high-performance cosmological N-body simulation code based on the PM method, implemented entirely on GPUs using the NVIDIA Warp framework. This Python-based library allows for the development of high-performance compute kernels with relative ease, lowering the barrier to entry for GPU programming. Our code is designed to rapidly evolve millions of particles from high redshift to the present day. We demonstrate its computational efficiency by benchmarking it against an equivalent multi-threaded CPU implementation, showcasing a dramatic reduction in runtime. Crucially, we also perform a rigorous physical validation of the simulation output. By comparing the final matter power spectrum, $P(k)$, with results from established, high-fidelity simulations, we quantify the accuracy of our code and characterize the physical regimes where it provides reliable predictions. This work establishes our GPU-accelerated PM code as a validated and powerful tool for the rapid generation of cosmological simulations, enabling new avenues for statistical cosmological inquiry.

